  "prompt": "Why does Audible.com take away all my credits when my membership expires? Didn't I pay for those credits last year?",
  "response": "When you subscribe to an Audible membership, you receive a certain number of credits each month (or year, depending on your membership plan) that can be used to purchase audiobooks. While you do pay for your membership, the credits are typically viewed as a benefit of being an active member. \n\nWhen your membership expires, you lose access to those credits because they are tied to your subscription status. Audible's policy is that credits do not roll over indefinitely; if you choose not to renew your membership, any unused credits are forfeited. This practice is common in many subscription services as a way to encourage continued membership.\n\nIf you have credits that you haven't used before your membership expires, it's often a good idea to use them before your account goes inactive. You may want to check Audible's terms of service for the most current details about credits and membership policies, as they can change.",
